!! MCP Server — Detailed Instructions

This tiddler describes how to use each tool provided by the TiddlyWiki MCP server. For a general overview, see [[MCP Basics]].

!! Setup

!!! Starting the Server

```
tiddlywiki ./mywiki --mcp
```

Replace `./mywiki` with the path to your wiki folder. The wiki folder must contain a `tiddlywiki.info` file. The `--mcp` command auto-loads the `tiddlywiki/filesystem` plugin for disk persistence if not already present.

!!! Registering with an AI client

See [[MCP Installation]] for `.mcp.json` setup (Claude Code) and [[MCP Gemini Configuration]] for Gemini CLI.

!!! Read-Write Mode

The server starts in ''readonly mode by default''. To enable write operations, add `rw` (or `readwrite`) after `--mcp`:

```
tiddlywiki ./mywiki --mcp rw
```

In readonly mode (the default), only read tools (`get_tiddler`, `list_tiddlers`, `run_filter`, `render_tiddler`, `render_field`, `render_text`, `inspect_tree`, `inspect_pos`, `inspect_scope`, `inspect_tw`, `get_wiki_info`, `reload_tiddlers`) are available. `resave_tiddler` and `reload_mcp_modules` are write tools and require `rw`.

!!! Label

Give your MCP server instance a name to identify it in the `.tw-mcp/connect` discovery file. Useful when running multiple instances for different wikis or from different tools (e.g. VS Code, Claude CLI, terminal):

```
tiddlywiki ./mywiki --mcp label=vscode
```

The label appears in the `.tw-mcp/connect` JSON and helps distinguish which process created the pipe.

!!! Path Restrictions

By default, file operations are restricted to the wiki's `tiddlers/`, `files/`, and `output/` subdirectories. You can override this with:

```
tiddlywiki ./mywiki --mcp allowed-paths=/path/one,/path/two
```

---

!! Transports

The server runs two transports simultaneously:

!!! stdio

Standard input/output — the primary transport used by Claude CLI and other MCP clients. Messages are newline-delimited JSON-RPC 2.0.

!!! Named Pipe

A local named pipe for helper tools (like `tw-upload`). On startup, the server:

# Generates a 256-bit random authentication token
# Creates a named pipe (`\\.\pipe\tiddlywiki-mcp-<wiki-id>` on Windows, `.mcp.sock` on Unix)
# Writes a `.tw-mcp/connect` discovery file to the wiki directory:

```json
{"pipe":"\\\\.\\pipe\\tiddlywiki-mcp-...","token":"<hex>","pid":12345,"label":"vscode","command":"node tiddlywiki.js ..."}
```

Pipe clients must send the token in the `_auth_token` field of their `initialize` request. The `pid` field lets clients verify the server process is still alive. The `label` field (if present) identifies which instance created the pipe. The `command` field shows the full command line that started the server.

On exit, the server cleans up the pipe and discovery file.

---

!! Reading Tiddlers

!!! `get_tiddler`

Retrieves a single tiddler by title. By default returns ''metadata only'' (all fields except `text`) to save tokens. Set `detailed` to `true` to include the text field.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`title` |yes |The tiddler title |
|`format` |no |`hashline` (default) — text with hash anchors for editing. `tid` — plain `.tid` text without hashes. `json` — structured fields object |
|`detailed` |no |Set to `true` to include the `text` field (default: `false`) |

> ''Note:'' System tiddlers (`$:/` prefix) should only be fetched when explicitly requested by the user. The AI is instructed not to fetch system tiddlers for general queries.

''Example prompts:''

* "Show me the tiddler called GettingStarted"
* "Show me the full contents of MyTiddler" — triggers `detailed=true`

!!! `list_tiddlers`

Lists tiddler titles. By default returns up to 100 ''non-system'' tiddlers.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`tag` |no |Filter results to tiddlers with this tag |
|`limit` |no |Maximum number of results (default: 100) |
|`includeSystem` |no |Set to `true` to include `$:/` system tiddlers |
|`plugin` |no |List tiddlers inside a plugin (e.g. `$:/plugins/tiddlywiki/internals` or `$:/core`) |
|`overwrittenShadows` |no |List shadow tiddlers that have been overwritten by real tiddlers |

When listing large sets (plugins with thousands of tiddlers), results are grouped into a ''namespace summary'' — showing top-level namespaces with counts in parentheses (e.g. `config/ (252)`). You can then drill into specific namespaces using `run_filter` with a prefix.

''Example prompts:''

* "List all tiddlers tagged Journal"
* "Show me the first 20 tiddlers"
* "Show me all core tiddlers" — uses `plugin=$:/core`
* "Show me the overwritten shadow tiddlers"

!!! `run_filter`

Runs a [[TiddlyWiki filter expression|https://tiddlywiki.com/static/Filters.html]] and returns matching titles.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`filter` |yes |A TiddlyWiki filter expression |

> ''Important:'' Always include `!is[system]` as the ''first'' operator in filters (unless system tiddlers are explicitly requested). This narrows the working set early and avoids unnecessary processing of thousands of system/shadow tiddlers.

When results exceed 100, the output switches to a ''namespace summary'' — grouping titles by common prefix with counts. This lets you progressively drill into large result sets by narrowing the prefix filter.

''Namespace browsing pattern:''

# Start broad: `[all[shadows+tiddlers]prefix[$:/config/]]` → namespace summary with counts
# Drill in: `[all[shadows+tiddlers]prefix[$:/config/shortcuts/]]` → individual tiddlers
# Get details: use `get_tiddler` on a specific title

> ''Tip:'' Use `all[shadows+tiddlers]` to include shadow tiddlers (from plugins/core). Many important tiddlers are shadows that won't appear with just `prefix[]`.

''Example prompts:''

* "Find all tiddlers containing the word 'recipe'" — uses `[!is[system]search[recipe]]`
* "List tiddlers modified today" — uses `[!is[system]days:modified[-1]]`
* "Show tiddlers tagged 'Project' sorted by title" — uses `[tag[Project]sort[title]]`
* "Show me config tiddlers including shadows" — uses `[all[shadows+tiddlers]prefix[$:/config/]]`
* "Show me all core UI tiddlers" — uses `[all[shadows+tiddlers]prefix[$:/core/ui/]]`

!!! `render_tiddler`

Renders a tiddler's wikitext to plain text or HTML. Supports all global macros (including `list-links`, `list-links-draggable`, etc.) through the ~TiddlyWiki page macro import system.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`title` |yes |The tiddler title to render |
|`type` |no |`text/plain` (default), `text/plain-formatted`, or `text/html` |
|`mode` |no |`raw` (default) — render through type parser. `viewtemplate` — render through the ~ViewTemplate body cascade (same as the story river) |

> ''Token efficiency:'' Plain text output (`text/plain` or `text/plain-formatted`) is significantly smaller than HTML — roughly 5–6× fewer tokens for the same content. Prefer plain text unless the HTML structure is specifically needed. Dynamic wikitext (macros, filters, transclusions) is fully resolved in all output modes.

''Example prompts:''

* "Render the GettingStarted tiddler"
* "Render the TableOfContents as HTML"
* "Render the Filter Operators tiddler" — resolves dynamic tag-based filter tables server-side

!!! `render_text`

Renders arbitrary wikitext with full context — global macros, procedures, and variables are all available. Use `\import` to pull in procedures from other tiddlers. Useful for testing wikitext snippets, executing procedures that gather information, or generating content dynamically.

Also supports `parsetree` output for structural analysis of wikitext before macro expansion.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`text` |yes |The wikitext to render |
|`type` |no |Input text type (default: `text/vnd.tiddlywiki`) |
|`output` |no |`text/plain` (default), `text/plain-formatted`, `text/html`, or `parsetree` |
|`context` |no |Tiddler title to use as context (sets `currentTiddler` variable) |
|`exclude` |no |Keys to omit from `parsetree` output (e.g. `['start','end']`) |
|`include` |no |Keys to unfold in `parsetree`. `text` is compact by default — use `['text']` to expand. |

> ''Note:'' Action widgets (like `action-setfield`, `action-sendmessage`) do NOT execute server-side. Only rendering/transclusion works.

For widget tree analysis, use [[inspect_tree|MCP Source Position Tracking]]. For source position tracking, use [[inspect_pos|MCP Source Position Tracking]].

''Example prompts:''

* "Render this wikitext: `<<version>>`" — returns the TiddlyWiki version string
* "Show me the value of `{{$:/palette}}`" — transcludes a system tiddler value
* "Run this filter inline: `{{{ [tag[Journal]count[]] }}}`" — evaluates a filtered transclusion

''Example — importing procedures from another tiddler:''

You can use `\import` to pull in procedures defined in other tiddlers and then call them:

```
\import [[$:/some/tiddler-with-procedures]]
<<my-procedure "argument">>
```

''Example — gathering wiki settings:''

```
TiddlyWiki Version: <<version>>
Current palette: {{$:/palette}}
Current theme: {{$:/theme}}
Plugins: {{{ [has[plugin-type]sort[]] :map[{!!version}addprefix[ - ]addprefix<currentTiddler>] +[join[, ]] }}}
```

!!! `render_field`

Renders a single tiddler field or data index as wikitext. Useful for compound tiddlers where you need to render individual field values without fetching the text first.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`title` |yes |The tiddler title |
|`field` |no |Field name to render (default: `text`) |
|`index` |no |Data tiddler index (alternative to `field`) |
|`output` |no |`text/html` (default), `text/plain`, or `text/plain-formatted` |

''Example prompts:''

* "Render the body field of TestMF" — uses `field="body"`
* "Preview the aaa entry of TestMF" — uses `index="aaa"`

!!! `inspect_tree`

Analyzes the rendered widget tree structure. Returns type counts (for the full tree regardless of depth, including transclusions), link targets, and a depth-limited JSON representation.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`text` |yes |The wikitext to analyze |
|`type` |no |Input text type (default: `text/vnd.tiddlywiki`) |
|`context` |no |Context tiddler (sets `currentTiddler`) |
|`exclude` |no |Attribute names to omit from the tree |
|`include` |no |Keys to unfold. `text` is compact by default — use `['text']` to expand. |
|`depth` |no |Max depth for tree JSON output (default: 3) |

''Example prompts:''

* "How many links are in the About tiddler?" — type counts show `12 link`
* "Show me the widget tree for `<<list-links>>`" — shows macro expansion structure
* "What transclusions are in GettingStarted?" — shows transclude nodes with targets

!!! `inspect_pos`

Renders wikitext to HTML with compact `p=` position attributes and a title index header. Each `p` attribute has the format `idx:start-end` where `idx` references the title index. SVG elements are stripped of position data for token efficiency.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`text` |yes |The wikitext to render |
|`type` |no |Input text type (default: `text/vnd.tiddlywiki`) |
|`context` |no |Context tiddler (sets `currentTiddler`) |

Use the output with `inspect_scope` to examine variables at specific positions.

''Example prompts:''

* "Show me the source positions in the Quick Start tiddler" — renders HTML with `p=` position attributes
* "Where does the Download button come from?" — trace `p="2:81-84"` back to `$:/cards/procedures` via the title index

!!! `inspect_scope`

Inspects the variable scope at a specific source position in rendered wikitext. Renders the text, finds the widget at the given character position, and returns all variables in scope — ordered innermost first (local variables before globals).

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`tiddler` |no |Tiddler title to render (resolve from the title index header) |
|`text` |no |Wikitext to render instead (for rendering from the caller's perspective) |
|`charPos` |no |Character position within the text field |
|`context` |no |Context tiddler (sets `currentTiddler`) |
|`match` |no |Match widget by variable values to disambiguate repeated positions (e.g. `{"currentTiddler": "Quick Start: Desktop"}`) |
|`filter` |no |Only show variables matching this substring |
|`limit` |no |Max variables to show (default: 20) |
|`all` |no |Set to `true` to show all variables |

> ''Tip:'' When inspecting a position inside a macro/procedure, render from the ''caller's'' wikitext (using the `text` parameter) rather than the definition tiddler. This gives you the full scope including `currentTiddler`, `thisTiddler`, and procedure parameters.

''Example prompts:''

* "Inspect the scope at the flex-card button" — shows procedure params, currentTiddler, etc.
* "What variables are available at L81@$:/cards/procedures for the Desktop card?" — uses `match` to select the right list iteration
* "Show me only card-related variables" — uses `filter: "card"`

For a comprehensive guide to the source position tracking workflow, see [[MCP Source Position Tracking]].

!!! `inspect_tw`

Inspects TiddlyWiki's internal `$tw` object structure. Navigate the runtime object tree, view function source code, and call functions to inspect their return values. Results are automatically depth-reduced if they exceed 10K characters. All `$tw.utils.*` functions are callable in addition to the wiki read functions.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`path` |no |Dot-separated path into `$tw` (e.g. `wiki`, `boot.wikiInfo`, `utils`). Empty string = top-level keys |
|`depth` |no |How many levels deep to inspect (default: 1). Start at 1, go deeper based on `maxDepth` in response |
|`fullSource` |no |Set to `true` to show full function source code instead of first 5 lines |
|`call` |no |Array of string arguments to call a function with and inspect the return value |
|`exclude` |no |Array of key names to skip (use to avoid large or circular branches like `wiki`) |

''Example prompts:''

* "Inspect $tw" — shows top-level keys of the `$tw` object
* "Inspect $tw.wiki" — shows wiki store methods and properties
* "Inspect $tw.boot.wikiInfo with depth 2" — shows wiki configuration in detail
* "Inspect $tw.wiki.addTiddler full" — shows full function source code
* "Inspect $tw.wiki.getTiddler(\"HelloThere\")" — calls the function and inspects the returned tiddler object
* "Inspect $tw.rootWidget with max detail but exclude wiki" — deep inspection, skipping the large wiki branch

For a comprehensive guide with output format explanation and more examples, see [[MCP Inspect Tool]].

!!! `get_wiki_info`

Returns pre-formatted wiki metadata including:

* Wiki title and subtitle (with macros rendered)
* Tiddler counts (standard, system, shadow, overridden shadows, tags)
* Installed plugins, themes, and languages (one per line)
* TiddlyWiki version
* Server status (readonly mode, filesystem adaptor)
* Basic settings from the ControlPanel/Basics panel (site title, username, default tiddlers, animation duration, journal settings, etc.)

Takes no parameters. The output is pre-formatted plain text — the AI presents it directly without reformatting.

''Example prompts:''

* "What plugins are installed?"
* "How many tiddlers are in this wiki?"
* "What are the current wiki settings?"

!!! `reload_tiddlers`

Re-reads tiddler files from disk into the in-memory store. Use this after editing `.tid` files externally (e.g. with a text editor or git pull).

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`scope` |no |`tiddlers` (default) — reload edition tiddlers. `shadows` — re-read plugins/core shadow tiddlers. `all` — both |

Use `scope="shadows"` to refresh shadow tiddlers from modified plugins without restarting the server.

''Safety:''

* ''Diff-based'' — compares each disk tiddler with the in-memory version field-by-field. Only tiddlers that have actually changed are updated in the store, avoiding unnecessary syncer activity.
* ''Deduplication'' — if the same title appears in multiple files on disk (e.g. a `.tid` and a `.webp.meta`), only the last-loaded version is used, matching TiddlyWiki's boot behavior.
* ''SyncFilter respected'' — uses the same `$:/config/SyncFilter` as TiddlyWiki's syncer to skip tiddlers that aren't normally synced (e.g. `$:/temp/`, `$:/state/`, `$:/status/`, `$:/boot/`, `$:/HistoryList`, `$:/core`).
* Reports counts: added, updated, unchanged, and skipped (filtered).

---

!! Writing Tiddlers

> ''Important:'' Write tools require `rw` mode (`--mcp rw`). The server starts in readonly mode by default.

!!! `put_tiddler`

Creates a new tiddler or updates an existing one. The tiddler is saved to disk as a `.tid` file.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`title` |yes |The tiddler title |
|`fields` |yes |Object with tiddler fields: `text`, `tags`, `type`, etc. |
|`overwrite` |no |Set to `true` to overwrite an existing tiddler (default: `false`) |

''Behaviour:''

* If the tiddler ''does not exist'', it is created with automatic `created` and `modified` timestamps.
* If the tiddler ''exists'' and `overwrite` is `false` (default), a ''new unique title'' is generated (e.g. "My Tiddler" becomes "My Tiddler 1"). The original tiddler is ''not'' modified.
* If the tiddler ''exists'' and `overwrite` is `true`, the existing tiddler is updated. The original `created` timestamp is preserved and `modified` is updated.
* Timestamps respect the `$:/config/TimestampDisable` configuration.

''Example prompts:''

* "Create a tiddler called Meeting Notes with text: Discussed project timeline"
* "Update the tiddler Daily Log with new text, overwrite it"

!!! `edit_tiddler`

Edits specific lines of a tiddler using hashline references. Much cheaper than `put_tiddler` for large tiddlers — only the changed lines are sent. Conflict detection is built-in: if the tiddler was modified since the AI last read it, hashes won't match and the edit is rejected with updated references.

''Workflow:''

# Read the tiddler with `get_tiddler(format="hashline")` — each line gets a 2-character hash anchor (e.g. `1#AB:line text`)
# Send edits referencing lines by their `LINE#HASH` anchor
# If hashes match, edits are applied. If not, a mismatch error shows the changed lines with updated hashes.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`title` |yes |The tiddler title |
|`edits` |no |Array of text-line edit operations using hashline anchors (omit if only changing fields) |
|`set_fields` |no |Object of fields to add or update (key: value). Does not affect `text` — use `edits` for text. |
|`delete_fields` |no |Array of field names to remove |

''Edit operations:''

|!Op |!Fields |!Description |
|`replace_line` |`pos`, `lines` |Replace a single line |
|`replace_range` |`pos`, `end`, `lines` |Replace an inclusive range of lines |
|`append_at` |`pos`, `lines` |Insert lines after the anchor |
|`prepend_at` |`pos`, `lines` |Insert lines before the anchor |

`pos` and `end` are `LINE#HASH` anchors (e.g. `"5#AB"`). `lines` is an array of new line strings.

''Example:''

```json
{
  "title": "MyTiddler",
  "edits": [
    {"op": "replace_line", "pos": "3#KV", "lines": ["This replaces line 3"]},
    {"op": "append_at", "pos": "7#MN", "lines": ["Inserted after line 7", "Second new line"]}
  ]
}
```

''Example prompts:''

* "Change line 3 of MyTiddler to say something else"
* "Add a new section after the introduction"

!!! `delete_tiddler`

Deletes a tiddler from the store and removes its `.tid` file from disk.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`title` |yes |The tiddler title to delete |

> ''Warning:'' This operation cannot be undone (unless you have a backup or version control). The AI is instructed to confirm before deleting.

''Example prompts:''

* "Delete the tiddler called old-draft"

!!! `resave_tiddler`

Rewrites a single tiddler's `.tid` file using the current `$:/config/FileSystemPaths`. The common use case: you edit `FileSystemPaths` and want a particular tiddler to migrate from its old path to the new rule's target directory ''without'' touching its timestamps or content.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`title` |yes |The tiddler title |
|`preserve_timestamps` |no |Keep `modified` and `modifier` unchanged (default: `true`). Set `false` to stamp current time and username. |
|`strip_redundant` |no |Drop `revision` and drop `type` when it equals `text/vnd.tiddlywiki` (default: `true`) |
|`dry_run` |no |Report the old path, computed new path, and fields that would be stripped; do not write (default: `false`) |

''Behaviour:''

* The new filepath is computed from the current `FileSystemPaths` against the tiddler's current fields. If it differs from the existing location, the old `.tid` (and `.tid.meta` sidecar, if any) is deleted after the new file is written successfully.
* If the path does not change, the file is simply rewritten in place — useful for stripping `revision` or a redundant `type` field without touching timestamps.
* Verification + rollback: the new file is re-read to confirm it contains the title header. On failure, both the store and the new file are rolled back.

''Refusals:''

|!Reason |!Trigger |
|Not found |no tiddler with that title |
|Shadow-only |no `$tw.boot.files` entry (tiddler lives only in a plugin/core) |
|Bundled plugin |`plugin-type` is `plugin`, `theme`, or `language` |
|Bundled in .multids |filepath ends in `.multids` — would shred the shared file |

''Example prompts:''

* "Resave the tiddler HelloThere" — rewrites in place or relocates if `FileSystemPaths` changed
* "Dry-run resave on MyTiddler" — shows old → new path without writing
* "Resave MyTiddler and update the timestamp" — sets `preserve_timestamps=false`

> For bulk relocation after editing `FileSystemPaths`, prefer running the standalone `re-save-tiddlers.js` script rather than looping `resave_tiddler` — a single MCP tool call per tiddler is not the right shape for a wiki-wide sweep.

!!! `reload_mcp_modules`

Hot-reloads the tw-mcp plugin during development — re-reads the plugin folder from disk and refreshes ALL its subtiddlers (JS AND non-JS — doc tiddlers, wikitext, CSS), then re-executes each JS module. Lets you iterate on handler code without restarting the server.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`skip_disk_reload` |no |Set to `true` to skip the `$tw.loadPlugin` step. Use only when the wiki store already has fresh plugin source (e.g., after a manual `reload_tiddlers`). Default: `false`. |

''Behaviour:''

* ''Phase 1'' — `$tw.loadPlugin` re-reads the plugin folder from disk, `$tw.wiki.addTiddler` replaces the plugin JSON tiddler, `readPluginInfo` + `registerPluginTiddlers` + `unpackPluginTiddlers` re-unpack the shadow tiddlers with fresh source.
* ''Phase 2'' — for every JS subtiddler with a `module-type`, `$tw.modules.titles[title].exports` is cleared and `$tw.modules.execute(title)` runs fresh. The next tool call picks up the new code via late-binding in `mcp-handlers.js`.
* Two modules (`mcp-tools.js`, `mcp-handlers.js`) get ''identity-preserving'' reload — their new exports are merged onto the existing object so `mcp-lib.js`'s captured references stay live. This is why schema changes in `mcp-tools.js` are visible on the NEXT client connection without restart.

''Excluded modules — still require a full server restart:''

|!Module |!Reason |
|`mcp.js` |Command module, runs once at boot |
|`mcp-lib.js` |Holds the dispatcher, pipe server, stdin listener |
|`shared.js` |Holds `readonlyMode` and `checkPathAllowed` init context |
|`filesystem.js` |Holds the `reload_tiddlers` change listener |

''When to use what:''

|!Scenario |!Action |
|Edited an edition tiddler (`.tid` file on disk) |`reload_tiddlers` (scope=`tiddlers`) |
|Edited a non-JS subtiddler in tw-mcp (doc/wikitext/CSS) |`reload_mcp_modules` |
|Edited a JS handler in tw-mcp |`reload_mcp_modules` |
|Edited `mcp-lib.js`, `mcp.js`, `shared.js`, or `filesystem.js` |Full server restart |

''Safety:'' If a reloaded module throws during re-execution, the old `exports` object is restored so a bad edit doesn't brick the server — but you still won't be able to proceed past a syntax error; check the tool response for the error list.

''Example prompts:''

* "Reload the MCP plugin" — user just edited a handler and wants to test
* "Pick up my changes without restarting" — same intent, informal
* "Reload with skip_disk_reload" — when the wiki store was already refreshed via `reload_tiddlers`

!!! `upload_file`

Uploads a base64-encoded binary file to the wiki's `files/` directory and creates a canonical tiddler referencing it via `_canonical_uri`.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`filename` |yes |Filename to save (e.g. `photo.png`). No path separators allowed. |
|`data` |yes |Base64-encoded file content |
|`type` |yes |MIME type (e.g. `image/png`, `application/pdf`) |
|`title` |no |Tiddler title (defaults to filename) |
|`tags` |no |Space-separated tags |
|`subfolder` |no |Subfolder within `files/` (e.g. `images`) |

!!! `save_wiki_folder`

Exports the entire wiki as a wiki folder structure to a specified directory.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`path` |yes |Output directory path (must be empty or non-existent) |
|`filter` |no |Filter for tiddlers to include (default: `[all[tiddlers]]`) |
|`explodePlugins` |no |Set to `no` to keep plugins as single tiddlers (default: `yes`) |

''Example prompts:''

* "Export this wiki to /tmp/my-wiki-backup"

!!! `build_wiki`

Renders the wiki as a single standalone HTML file.

|!Parameter |!Required |!Description |
|`output` |yes |Output file path for the HTML file |
|`template` |no |Template tiddler (default: `$:/core/save/all`) |

''Example prompts:''

* "Build the wiki as output.html"

